solutions.content:
1. The algorithm will look as follows:

1. We create a queue, in which we add the root nodes of both trees.

1. As long as the queue is not empty, retrieve an element from the beginning of the queue:

1. If the elements are null, then move on to the next element in the queue.

1. If the node values are not equal, the trees are not identical.

1. If the node values are equal, then add the left and right children for both nodes to the queue.

1. If all nodes pass the check, then the trees are identical.

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    public boolean isSameTree(TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {
        Queue<TreeNode> queue = new LinkedList<>();
        queue.offer(p);
        queue.offer(q);

        while(!queue.isEmpty()) {
            TreeNode node1 = queue.poll();
            TreeNode node2 = queue.poll();

            if (node1 == null && node2 == null) {
                continue;
            }

            if (node1 == null || node2 == null) {
                return false;
            }

            if (node1.val != node2.val) {
                return false;
            }

            queue.offer(node1.left);
            queue.offer(node2.left);
            queue.offer(node1.right);
            queue.offer(node2.right);
        }

        return true;
    }
}
```

