# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
__The Idea is to match all the nodes of one tree with the other one, and whenever there is no match possible, return false__

# Approach
__The idea her is to recursive map nodes of one tree with the nodes of the other tree__

>__Check if the nodes reach null together (base case),__ 
  If yes, return true
  Else, execute other statements 

>__Check if only either of the nodes reach an end point__
 If yes, Return false
 Else, execute other statements

>__If the nodes are not the end points, check if the values they are storing are same or not?__
If different, return false
Else, continue with the code

>Recursive structure: 
__[match the left subtree of the current node with the left subtree of the other current node]__
__&&  (logical operator)__
__[match the right subtree of the current node with the right subtree of the other current node]__

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(N) :- N => Number of nodes in the tree

- Space complexity:
O(1), ignoring the recursive stack, otherwise the space = O(N)

# Code
```
class Solution //100% faster, 95.24% better space
{
public:
    bool chc(TreeNode *p, TreeNode *q)
    {
        if (p == NULL && q == NULL) // If the node reach an endpoint together, say true
            return true;
        if (p == NULL && q != NULL || q == NULL && p != NULL) // If only either of the nodes reach an end point, say false
            return false;
        if (p->val != q->val) // If none of the nodes are at the end points but there values differ, say false
            return false;
        return (chc(p->left, q->left) && chc(p->right, q->right));   
        // && is used instead of & as it short circuits the condition
        // i.e. it stops checking the conditions when a false is received (in the case of &&)
        // and in the case of ||, it stops checking when a true value is received
    }
    bool isSameTree(TreeNode *p, TreeNode *q)
    {
        return chc(p, q);
    }
};
```

