# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
If root of p and q is same, then check again for the root of left subtree of p and q. Again repeat the same process until you reach NULL.
Repeat this process for the right subtrees also.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- We are following a bottom to top approach where we go to the bottom of the tree and then come to top and keep checking whether p and q are same or not. If at any point, they are not same, return false, otherwise keep returning true.
- Also if p and q both are NULL at the same time, then it will return true because it implies that both are equal.
But if either p is null or q is null (but not both at the same time), then it implies that they are not equal and we return false.
- Also note that at any point of time, if the actual value of p and q are not equal, then also we have to return false. Here, we cannot write `p!=q`. Instead, we have to write `p->val != q->val` because we have to compare the values of p and q, but `p!=q` will compare the pointers, which can obviously never be equal because both p and q are present at different memory locations, although the value present inside both of them maybe same.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
Because we traverse each node only once.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: Auxiliary $$O(n)$$
Because in the worst case i.e. for a skew tree, the maximum stack space required will be equal to total number of nodes.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isSameTree(TreeNode* p, TreeNode* q) {
        if(p == NULL && q == NULL){
            return true;
        }
        if(p == NULL || q == NULL){
            return false;
        }
        if(p->val!=q->val){
            return false;
        }
        bool l = isSameTree(p->left,q->left);    //left subtrees
        bool r = isSameTree(p->right,q->right);  //right subtrees
        return l&&r;
    }
};
```

